05195nam a22009375i 9780674246744DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742467447 a10.4159/97806742467442doi  a(DE-B1597)549762  a(OCoLC)1148875431  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aBUS0230002bisacsh  aQD 110qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/141285:1 aBoldizzoni, Francesco, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForetelling the End of Capitalism :bIntellectual Misadventures since Karl Marx /cFrancesco Boldizzoni. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Sitting on the Edge of Apocalypse -- tChapter Two. The Interwar Revival of Prophecy -- tChapter Three. Hopes Betrayed -- tChapter Four. The End of History and What Followed -- tChapter Five. Wanderings of the Predictive Mind -- tChapter Six. How Capitalism Survives -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIntellectuals since the Industrial Revolution have been obsessed with whether, when, and why capitalism will collapse. This riveting account of two centuries of failed forecasts of doom reveals the key to capitalism’s durability. Prophecies about the end of capitalism are as old as capitalism itself. None have come true. Yet, whether out of hope or fear, we keep looking for harbingers of doom. In Foretelling the End of Capitalism, Francesco Boldizzoni gets to the root of the human need to imagine a different and better world and offers a compelling solution to the puzzle of why capitalism has been able to survive so many shocks and setbacks. Capitalism entered the twenty-first century triumphant, its communist rival consigned to the past. But the Great Recession and worsening inequality have undermined faith in its stability and revived questions about its long-term prospects. Is capitalism on its way out? If so, what might replace it? And if it does endure, how will it cope with future social and environmental crises and the inevitable costs of creative destruction? Boldizzoni shows that these and other questions have stood at the heart of much analysis and speculation from the early socialists and Karl Marx to the Occupy Movement. Capitalism has survived predictions of its demise not, as many think, because of its economic efficiency or any intrinsic virtues of markets but because it is ingrained in the hierarchical and individualistic structure of modern Western societies. Foretelling the End of Capitalism takes us on a fascinating journey through two centuries of unfulfilled prophecies. An intellectual tour de force and a plea for political action, it will change our understanding of the economic system that determines the fabric of our lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCapitalismxHistory. 0aEconomic history. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  aBernie Sanders.  aBreakdown.  aCapital.  aCommunism.  aDemocratic socialism.  aDownfall.  aEngels.  aFuturology.  aJeremy Corbyn.  aKeynes.  aPrediction.  aProgress.  aProphecy.  aRevolution.  aSchumpeter.  aSocial democracy.  aSocial forecasting.  aSocialism.  aThird Way.  aUtopia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069005740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067424674440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674246744423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674246744/original  a978-3-11-069005-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEB